The number of Covid-19 cases continues to soar after data from the Health ministry showed that 109 patients were in intensive care units. Of the number, 23 were on ventilator support, while 72 were on supplemental oxygen, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement. Fourteen more patients were under observation. “Another 24 patients are separately on supplementary oxygen, all of them in the general wards,” Kagwe said. Some 731 more people tested positive for the virus from a sample size of 4,513 tests conducted in 24 hours. This represents a positivity of 16.1 per cent. The new cases comprised 691 Kenyans and 40 foreign nationals aged between one and 84. The country’s virus caseload now stands at 113,967 from 1,373,839 tests conducted to date. “Unfortunately, five patients have succumbed to the disease, pushing our cumulative fatalities to 1,918. Our sincere condolences to the families and friends who have lost their loved ones,” the CS said. The data also showed that 678 patients were in health facilities, while 2,129 were in home-based isolation and care. “Today, 191 patients have recovered from the disease, 25 from health facilities, while 166 are from home-based isolation and care. The total recoveries now stand at 88,596.” In terms of distribution of cases per county, Nairobi recorded 541, followed by Tharaka Nithi with 42, Machakos with 39, Kiambu with 26, Kajiado and Mombasa with 18 each, and Meru with nine. Other counties were Nyeri and Makueni with five each; Nakuru with four; Garissa with three; Kilifi, Kisii, Murang’a, Narok, Nyamira, Trans Nzoia and Uasin Gishu with two each; while Kisumu, Mandera, Migori, Nyandarua, Kirinyaga, Bomet and Wajir had one each. The ministry noted that as of Saturday, 9,144 frontline workers had been vaccinated in 40 counties since the exercise was launched on March 5. The state targets to vaccinate at least 1.25 million Kenyans by the end of June in its first phase of the drive. The data shows that Nairobi is leading, having vaccinated 2,020 people so far, followed by Uasin Gishu with 1,304 and Kisumu with 764.